 <body bgcolor="white">
  <a href="#1" id="1">
   The National Hurricane Center provided life-saving information
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   as Hurricane Hugo moved across the Caribbean toward the Carolinas.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Forecasters, with the aid of satellites and computers, calculated where the hurricane would strike
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   so that emergency operations could get underway in those areas.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The center personnel felt the word did not get out in the Caribbean,
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   but were reassured by the response in the Carolinas
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   where proper response probably saved hundreds or thousands of lives.
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   By the time Hugo hit Charleston the center's big job was done.
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   Early today there were no immediate reports of deaths despite widespread damage in Charleston and coastal South Carolina.
  </a>
